Have you ever seen so many varieties of poinsettias? Pointy petals (bracts!), and round ones, curly bracts and flat ones! Bright pink and peachy pink and coral with cream! White and chartreuse and even yellow! Orangey red, true red, deep red, burgundy! The list goes on and on and I find it so fascinating!

I think part of being a good artist is really taking notice of the details of the different varieties and appreciating the differences! Each little nuance could be painted in a different way!

I think it’s the gardener in me, too, that just finds all the different varieties so fascinating! And I love that poinsettia season gives us a great reason to go to the nursery in the winter! I get sooo inspired at the nursery! Makes me want to run right home and paint!!!

It’s been an amazing year! Immensely grateful for all the Lord has given me to put my hands to right in this house, particularly during a time when I can’t really go places! He is always faithful….in every season!

So grateful for this sweet studio I get to spend my days in and for all the beauty the Lord helps me to create here!

So grateful for the ability to share that with you here on the Gram, and also in your own homes, thanks to the business He’s blessed us with! Shipping my artwork out to so many of you has been such a joy and a blessing! Thank you! Bartley and I are so grateful!

Also grateful that the Lord led us to @unsifted.kc this year, and has been using freshly milled wheat to heal my liver (that was damaged from the IV nutrition that helped keep me alive before my transplant)! 

And I’m so grateful that He’s allowed me to share that here and that so many of you are now experiencing all sorts of health benefits and improvements, since starting to mill your own wheat!!

Goodness, He’s blessed us all so much, hasn’t He?!? Even when things are hard, He’s right here with us, carrying us through the tough stuff….if we’ll let Him. I don’t know about you, but I’d much rather lean on His strength, which is far greater than mine could ever hope to be!

Rather than making resolutions or even choosing a word for the year to focus on, I want my heart and mind to be squarely focused on HIM. The One who made every bit of this possible!

He has my heart and everything I have came from Him. 

“Every good and perfect gift is from above, coming down from the Father of lights, who does not change like shifting shadows.” James 1:17 CSB

Love you, friends! Looking forward to spending 2023 with you here!!

What’s something you’re looking forward to?

Happy New Year’s Eve, friends! Grateful for all God has done in 2022 and I’m excited to see what He has in store for 2023!

Have you been keeping up with the sock knitting chatter off and on in Stories over the last month-ish?😄

I finished up the last pair of socks I had on the needles last night! But I quickly realized what a blunder that was, because now I don’t have a project to work on until I cast on something new! 😂 That, of course, requires some thought and planning and prep (winding up yarn balls and such) before any actual knitting can begin! Which meaaaaans, that I’ve got work to do before I can relax with some knitting in the evenings!

Therefore, I’ve decided one should always keep a back up project on the needles….something in-progress to work on, even as you’re finishing and starting more projects! I shouldn’t have been in such a hurry to finish that last pair before casting on more! Haha!

I finally understand why so many knitters have multiple projects going at once! So even as you’re finishing projects, there’s always something else waiting for you to pick up and work on until you have time to cast on something new!😁

Anyway, now that church is over and lunch is done, there’s about to be a yarn ball Wind-a-thon and a Cast-On-apalooza over here, so I can get some new sock sets started! 😂 (And yes, I still need to order one more ball of yarn to finish my cardigan!😏)

Happy Sunday, friends! Enjoy your day of rest!

I packed up some large paintings for shipping last week and filmed a bit of the process to share with you in case you’re curious as to how we ship our art!

⭐️Every painting gets gift wrapped with brown paper, a pretty bow, 2 gift tags and a hand-written note!

⭐️Then the painting is wrapped in bubble wrap. The goal here isn’t aesthetics! I purposely don’t do proper gift-wrapped, neatly tucked corners with the bubble! Instead, I pull both layers of bubble up over the top corners of the painting to provide additional padding on those corners where they could get banged around easiest.

⭐️Next comes layers of cardboard (particularly for great big paintings) on top of the bubble on either side of the painting, to help protect it from being smooshed or being cut, should the box accidentally get punctured in transit.

⭐️Lastly, paper stuffing is added to the box to help keep the painting nestled securely in place, so it’s not sliding around in the box and getting banged up as it travels.

We put a lot of thought and effort into wrapping up artwork for shipping, because the goal is to get that painting to its new owner in perfect condition! I like to do all that I can to make sure that happens! Obviously, I can’t control what happens to it after it leaves the studio. That’s why I also do the following….!❤️

I like to use the time I’m wrapping and packing paintings up for shipping, to pray over the recipients of each box, thanking the Lord for them and for the blessing their purchase has been to us! I ask the Lord to keep the package safe as it travels, and pray that the artwork would be a blessing to all who see it. And I pray that it would remind the collectors of our great God and all that He’s done in my life….and all that He’s more than able to do in theirs!🙌🏻

Packing up art is another task that could be mundane but has turned into a way that I can do my best to honor the Lord with my time and with my work.❤️

Another benefit of using the timer if you’re a painter, is that it forces you to paint more loosely! You can’t get so sucked into every little detail if you want to beat the timer, so have to loosen up and hustle!

This is a great way to start your painting session, with a quick little warm up painting and a 30 minute timer!

The timer also works great as a motivator for all sorts of things, like if you’ve got a task that needs doing that you’ve been putting off, like cleaning or something! Set your timer and power through and I bet you’ll be surprised at how much you can get done when you’re focused on the task and working quickly to beat the clock!!

Send this reel to a creative buddy in your life!! Or maybe even do the timer challenge together!! Make a game out of it and see how much you can both get done in your 30 minutes!

Happy creating, friends!!

I’m definitely not an expert but this was something I never thought about as a newer gardener! Hopefully this little tip will help someone who might not have thought to do this already! 

Now that I’ve been doing this for years, I’ve learned that there’s usually a lot of spent blooms hiding under all of the healthy blooms. It’s nice that they sort of sink down into the plant so it doesn’t look so junky, but ultimately all of that spent stuff is just wasting your plant’s energy!

You can help your plant out a lot by removing all of those spent blooms and their little stem heads! This will give it loads more energy to produce lots more blooms! 🩵💚

I typically spend a little time deadheading each morning, and this has made a massive difference in how well our plants bloom! Try it! I bet it makes a huge difference for your plants, too!

Silicone baking mats for the win!!! 🏆 

As always, we let our amazing bread machine make the tortilla dough for us, using the @unsifted.kc tortilla recipe. That takes 22 minutes and when the dough is ready, I divide it into 12 balls and press each one between wax paper in our cast iron tortilla press (so they don’t stick to the press). That makes about a 6” tortilla. However, we like larger tortillas, so I then transfer them to the counter to roll out even more with my rolling pin. Typically, I use wax paper or parchment paper but both can wrinkle and tear your dough. I’ve also used a ziplock bag that’s split open, but it’s sometimes not quite big enough.

Using these 12”x16” baking mats worked perfectly! (I can send you the link if you need it. They’re also linked in my Amazon storefront, which is linked in my bio.)

Being able to see through the mats, let’s you see the tortilla so you can maintain their circular shape as you roll them. And because the mats have a little weight to them, they keep the tortillas from shrinking up. They also don’t wrinkle or tear the dough, like the other things I’ve used can do.

Once they’re rolled out to 11 or 12”, I transfer them to a skillet where my hubby cooks them for about 40 seconds per side. 

Special thanks to my sweet friend @brookeannettebroadbent, who sparked the idea when she shared that she was rolling out the new @unsifted.kc graham cracker recipe between two silicone baking mats!

So happy that this made our tortilla making process completely frustration-free today!!👍🏻

Doing these two things doesn’t have to take a long time, but doing them every day can make a world of difference for your plants!!

See my two previous deadheading reels for tips on what to look for when deadheading! (It’s more than just pulling off spent blooms!!)😉

As for watering, take a peek at your plants in the evening, after you’ve watered in the morning and then they spent the day in the sun. How do they look?

If the leaves have turned yellow, that likely means they got a bit too much water. 

What’s more likely though, is that they may look brown or wilty. That means they want more water. So tomorrow when you give them a drink, try giving them a bit more than you did the day before and then check them again at the end of the day, to see how well they fared that day. 

It may take several days of watering to get a feel for how much each of your plants wants to drink. For instance, I’ve learned over time that our alyssum plants want like 3 times as much water as everything else! Now that I know, I can give them what they need each day!

Also, watering and deadheading can be fun tasks for kiddos in the summer! They can learn what a spent bloom looks like compared to a new bud and how to tell the difference! And removing spent blooms can become a bit of a scavenger hunt or even a contest to see which plant has the most spent blooms each day!

Also, there’s just nothing like the joy of watching something grow — up close and personal — and the thrill of knowing you helped to care for that plant and helped it to thrive! A very good thing indeed, for kiddos to feel!🩵💚

I know lots of you are experienced gardeners and this is all pretty intuitive for you! But I hope this is helpful for those of you who may be new to caring for plants or are struggling to keep yours happy in the heat!

I know lots of you, like me, have begun baking with freshly milled wheat flour in the last year or two, and I’ve heard from some who struggle with shaping things like breads, dinner rolls, etc. 

I shared a reel on how I shape hamburger buns, so check that out if you missed it!

Our bread machine will bake a 2-pound loaf start to finish if we want it to. Just dump everything in and 2-1/2 hours or so later, you’ve got a jumbo loaf of bread. 

Most of the time, however, I prefer to shape the dough myself and that way I can divide it into two, more standard sized 1-pound loaves. So I let the bread machine make the dough and do the first rise for me, and then, I divide it up and shape it myself. 

NOTE: I purposely did not edit out any of the shaping of this loaf so you can see that this process took me 31 seconds to shape that one loaf!! This is not a long, hard process! You can do this! And often, I find that the less I fiddle with it, the better it turns out! So keep it quick and don’t fuss too much!

Regarding Rise Times: Keep in mind that rise times will need to vary depending on the weather & humidity — YES, even in a temperature controlled home! Your dough knows what’s up with the weather 😄 and will be impacted by it, so adjust your rise times accordingly! Rise times may need to be longer in the colder months and shorter when it’s hot & humid.

BAKING TIP: I baked these for 18 minutes and then laid aluminum foil over the top and baked for another 5 minutes. The foil helps the crust to stay a bit softer and not get too brown, but this step is totally optional!

ALSO: You can brush your loaves with egg wash before baking for a shiny finish or you can brush them with butter when they come out of the oven, to keep the crust a bit softer. Both are optional and for reference, I didn’t opt to brush these with anything.

I hope this visual and these tips are helpful to you!!

What. A. Morning!!!!😭🙌🏻

The song says it all….The Lord has been SO GOOD to us! He’s carried us through another very challenging season!

We got word from my transplant team that they, in agreement with the transplant infectious disease team, don’t feel like we need to stay isolated at home any more!! We still have to be cautious and act like it’s flu season (masks, hand washing, sanitizing, etc) but were able to go back to church this morning for the first time in almost 3-1/2 YEARS! Let’s just say there were definitely some happy tears!!!😉

We are SO grateful for our church’s livestream of the services each week, so we could continue to worship “together” with our church family but Bartley and me standing and singing in the living room along with the livestream is wayyyyy different than being in the same room with other believers and worshipping together!! 

What a joy it was!!! The mask is a hassle, of course, but small price to pay to be able to go to church in person again! 

(For those wondering, I take anti-rejection meds to protect my small intestine transplant, however they severely compromise my immune system. That’s why we have to be so careful, because I’m more at risk of catching illnesses. And if I did, and couldn’t keep those anti-rejection meds level in my system, my transplant would be at risk of organ rejection. That could be a life and death situation at that point.) 

Anyway, I’ve barely been anywhere in the last 3 years and 5 months so it felt SO crazy to be out among the people this morning! So many emotions, for sure!

But above them all, GRATITUDE. HE HAS BEEN SO GOOD TO ME!!🙌🏻 Thank you, Lord!!

Making our own pizza crust has been a GAME CHANGER on pizza night!! 

Because we’re using freshly milled wheat flour to make these crusts, we’re getting 40 of the 44 nutrients a body needs in order to thrive…..all in our crust!!🙌🏻 

(Read more details about the benefits of freshly milled wheat at @unsifted.kc!!)

Pizza night is our favorite night of the week because it’s not only super delicious but also, super nutritious!

We use the @unsifted.kc Simple Sandwich recipe for our pizza crusts (and sandwich bread, hamburger buns, dinner rolls, and even cinnamon rolls!).

We par-bake the crusts at 400° for 10 minutes. 

To wrap them for freezing, we wrap them in a layer of Saran Wrap followed by a layer of Press ‘n Seal. 

On pizza night, we let them thaw on the counter (only takes maybe 30 minutes!) and then load them up with our favorite toppings.

We bake the pizzas at 450° for 12 minutes. 

By doing it this way, we’re able to make three crusts every time we make pizza crust, so that lasts us for three weeks of pizza nights! And by freezing the baked crust, we’ve locked in all of that nutrition without having to bake crust every single week! 🎉

Painting over things is ok! 

Yes, I spent hours painting those paintings a couple years ago. But that was a couple YEARS AGO!!

And I’ve spent hours and hours and HOURS painting and practicing and growing since then!

Hopefully anything I paint now, will be an improvement over what I painted in the past!

And I think there’s value in being able to look at our past work with humility and recognize that not everything we create will be a masterpiece every single time! 😁 And that’s ok! That’s reality! 

There’s honesty in that and there’s freedom in that!

There’s freedom in knowing that if it wasn’t a masterpiece or it didn’t stir someone’s heart enough to move anyone to want to buy it, then it can be painted over because hopefully the next painting will!

And if a painting has been sitting here for a couple years, it’s not doing anyone any good hidden in a stack in the corner. Time to get it out and give it some love again!

Hopefully each new piece I paint will be something beautiful that someone will be drawn to and want to have for their own home!

Painting over something is not a bad thing, friends!❤️😘

It reminds me of my first few years as a knitter. If I messed up and had to rip back on my knitting and knit it again, it felt like the absolute worst thing! But after knitting for 12 years now, I know that knitting back just helps me to get it right the next time and it gives me more practice knitting as I knit it again! Both are very good things!

I don’t ever want to cling so tightly to something I painted in the past, that I can’t see it with honest eyes and recognize when it might be time for a do-over!

Hope that encourages you, friends!🩵💚

Whenever I need to take photos of cards I’ve made to share here, I love to gather pretty props to enhance the photos. I thought I’d share a few tips for those of you who may have some sort of product photos that you take and share, as well. 

These are a few things I keep in mind when gathering props:

🌟 I look for items around the house that have complimentary colors and will coordinate with the cards or the seasonal theme. I’m not looking for “matchy-matchy” but I AM looking for complimentary!

🌟 Often, the items I gather have nothing to do with that particular season or theme. I’m just going for the color theme! A photo can have a decidedly Fall feel (for instance) without a single leaf or mum or pumpkin in sight, depending on the colors and textures of the items you use!

🌟 I often try to incorporate a variety of textures. Woods and fabric, vintage books and hankies, etc. Think hard and soft.

🌟 I love to pull in some vintage items to make my photos truly unique! No one else has many of my exact antiques!

🌟 I’m not afraid to use items that are a little rusty or a little chippy! That just adds interest and character to each photo!

🌟 I also like to pull in a few crafty supplies in the same color scheme. Things like ink pads, pens, ribbons, washi, blending brushes, etc all work well. 

🌟 I gather items that are small in size, realizing that even then, I may only show bits and pieces or corners of these items in the final photos. 

🌟 Remember, the card (or whatever product you’re photographing) is to be the star of the photo, so I don’t want to use any items that are SO eye catching that they detract attention from the star!

Are there things you take photos of to share online, that you could implement some of these tips on?

Yes there is work to be done and yes, the Lord has given me this job so He expects me to do the work, but ultimately, it’s all His! So asking Him to guide and direct every bit of it, will ensure it’s success!

Now, that success may not look like what WE might think it should. But we can know for sure that if we’re giving Him the control and asking Him to steer the ship, we can’t fail! He’ll bless it in whatever ways He chooses and we can be confident that He will work all things for His glory and for our good!

And on days when my to-do list is LONG or the tasks seem too difficult or we might face challenges of various kinds, I can remind myself of the truth from God’s Word that promises that “I can do all things through Christ, because he gives me strength.” That’s found in Philippians 4:13.

I don’t have to fret over every little detail! I just have to do the thing He’s put in front of me to do, and then do next thing and then the thing after that, all the while listening for His leading and doing my best to follow His direction.

Y’all….these dahlias feel like a miracle! If you’ve followed along in stories then you might know that last year, we’d never even heard of a thing called spider mites & before we figured it out, they’d attacked & decimated our entire dahlia bed!😭

This year, we came in to the gardening season with a bit more knowledge! We knew what to look for should they ever come back, but didn’t know we should be preventing them. Our hot, dry garden was their ideal home & when they showed up again, we were already behind because they were multiplying & doing tons of damage faster than we could fight them!

BUT, we did not give up! We found a @gardenanswer video on YouTube with tons of info & we went to war against those spider mites!

We’ve fought hard! I began pruning & removing decaying junk from the plants DAILY. Bart has been spraying the plants with water (even up under the leaves) DAILY because spider mites don’t like it wet. And WEEKLY, Bart has been spraying with some of the safer things she recommended for eliminating them. 

It’s been a battle but we are WINNING, praise the Lord!

I love that the Lord has given me a visual reminder that our great God goes to battle for US! He is our Defender! Literally, our defense against a very real enemy who the Bible tells us, is out to steal, kill & destroy us.

He is our Provider!! Just like we’ve provided nourishment for those plants, He provides for our every need!

He is our Protector! Just like we have been for our beloved dahlias! 

He is our Hope for the future! Just like we’ve been for the dahlias! Without us going to battle for them, they would have been destroyed. 

But our faithful Master Gardener lovingly tends to us continually, with more love & care than we can fathom! He wants us to thrive! To grow & BLOOM, not just barely hang on. John 15:8 tells us that God gets more glory when we bear much fruit, so why would He not want that for us?

Our dahlias didn’t know what to do on their own (obv, since they’re not human🤪). We don’t have to have all the answers to our problems, either. But we can REST in knowing that we can trust the One who does! Even when things are hard! He has a GOOD plan for your life!!❤️

Y’all. My transplant team decided it was time for me to travel back to DC this week for a follow up, including a colonoscopy. 

For the new crowd, I had a small intestine transplant almost 6 years ago (next week!!) and typically with this super rare transplant, patients have a colonoscopy annually, to make sure everything is still looking as it should. 

In my case, they didn’t feel like it was safe for me to travel being immune compromised. So I’ve gotten a pass for the last several years & was quite happy about it!😂

The last time I had a colonoscopy in 2019, I had an allergic reaction to the prep you have to drink or possibly the crystal light they said to put in the prep. I’ve assumed it was the crystal light, since that was the first time I’d ever had it. 

Turns out…I now have a new allergy to add to the list of allergies I’ve developed since I got so sick years ago. It now appears I have a PEG allergy (acronym for the main ingredient in most preps). 

We flew to DC on Wednesday & I started drinking the prep around 6pm. They’d prescribed a different one from last time, AND had me pre-medicate with benedryl to hopefully ward off any reaction. 

It became clear in the middle of the night, that I was having an allergic reaction! Again! Thankfully, I had benedryl on board so that lessened the effects but gosh, we were afraid they’d admit me to the hospital & push back the procedure like they did in 2019 (it was a nightmare)! 

The happy ending is that they went ahead with the procedure as scheduled, but have now determined I’m allergic to the prep. (We suggested they never make me go through it again 😂 but they assured us there are other prep options with different ingredients.😏)

I’m feeling much better now tho not 💯, so still taking benedryl as we head home today. It’s also been a whole week of crazy pre-procedure diet (including no wheat!!😫) so we are SO ready to go home!

SO grateful the Lord has seen us through another difficult challenge! He’s SO GOOD to us ALWAYS, even when things are hard!🙌🏻

Much love, friends! I’ve missed you!

PS. It was SO FUN telling my docs about the benefits of freshly milled wheat, with proof of it in my lab reports!!🎉

Painting more than 100 floral Christmas ornaments over just a few weeks time taught me that it’s really true when they tell you that practice and repetition will help you go grow in your craft…..whatever that craft is!

You’re building up a sort of creative muscle memory when you do a thing over and over and over again and the things that maybe were a struggle for you to do in the beginning become a lot easier after the 50th, 100th or 500th time you’ve done it!!

In the case of painting florals, you get a lot more proficient with painting basic flower shapes, so that after a jillion of them, now your brain doesn’t have to work so hard at the basics and can focus more on the details like light and shading and color. 

While painting this next floral collection on canvas, I’m quite a bit more free with my approach to each flower. My brush strokes are more confident and that shows in the finished piece…..and that thrills me because it’s growth in my work that I can actually SEE. 🙌🏻 And not only that, but goodness, I’m enjoying the process!

If you’re feeling stuck creatively, try something new!

If you’re a painter who always paints small, maybe try painting larger! Or try a different medium!

If you’re a paper crafter, pull out some stamps or dies you’ve rarely (or maybe never😉) used and try them out!

If you’re a knitter or embroiderer or whatever else, learn a new technique! YouTube offers a wealth of inspiration and instruction!

Regardless of what your “thing” is, there are times in everyone’s life when inspiration seems in short supply! The stresses of daily life can press in and take up residence in our minds, where creativity once abounded and suddenly there’s not much room for creative energy to spark and for ideas to flow. 

That’s when it’s time to try something new! And that could literally be as simple as going outside for a walk! Just a change of scenery can often help to shake things loose and inspiration to start flowing!

Here are a few more ideas you might try, to get your creativity back on track!

✨ Try a new color scheme! (This always helps me!)
✨ Try doing the opposite of your norm - if you always paint a bright underpainting, go dark or pastel!
✨ Reorganize your supplies! Sometimes just organizing can cause a couple random spools of thread or tubes of paint to end up next to each other in the process, and a new idea might come to mind!
✨ Flip through some magazines or books that you find inspiring - that are NOT about the same topic you’re feeling stuck in! Perhaps a home decor magazine or a pretty recipe book. Often, inspiration comes when studying something totally unrelated!
✨ Tidy up your workspace! This is a big one for me. If I’m swimming in a mess, it makes it very difficult to feel creative freedom!
✨ Take a NAP! For real! I don’t recommend this every day 😂 but sometimes, a bit of extra rest is all you’re lacking to get those creative juices flowing again!

I’ve often found that doing nothing, produces nothing!😆 Profound, I know. 😁 

But it’s true! If you want to get your creativity unstuck, you’re probably gonna need to take some steps forward to help that to happen! 

What’s something you do to feel creative again? Share in the comments to help each other!✨

Packaging all of the Christmas treats I baked up was so much fun!! 

I started by gathering up all my supplies! Ribbon for bows around each mini loaf, gift tags with each family’s name on the back, lots of die cuts to add to the cuteness, and even some die cut paper “ribbon” trim!

I started by assembling all the boxes and adding two sheets of holiday striped wax paper to the bottom of each box. TIP: Alternating the direction of the stripes on each layer, creates the look of a holiday plaid!

Then I tucked one pumpkin loaf into the back half of each box and added the cookies to the front half. Two each of four different kinds of cookie: oatmeal, chocolate chip, peanut butter and speculaas (windmill cookies). I love that since I used freshly milled wheat flour in all of it, they’re not only delicious but they’ve got some good nutrition, too! (See more about wheat nutrition at @unsifted.kc!) 

Once the cookies were in and I closed the boxes up, I added a strip of die cut paper ribbon to the top and then tied a bow around the whole box. 

Next, I tucked a couple leaf and pine die cuts under the bow and then tied on the tags with a sparkly die cut snowflake attached! (@the_greetery) 

Everything I piled on except for the bow, is all just paper! This makes it super cost effective but all of that fun color and detail makes them so cute and adds so much visual interest!

As I mentioned in my reel about baking everything up, I’ve wanted to make cookie boxes for about 30 years now 🤣 since I first saw Martha Stewart make some on her show when I was a teenager! I’m SO happy that I’ve finally learned how to bake and we could share some treats with others!

I have to say, cleaning up has never been more fun!😁 

I was able to turn tidying up into a fun creative exercise by corralling all the leftover bits and pieces of gift wrapping toppings into a vintage soda crate! The end result of cleaning up is something styled to be super cute and inspiring, and it makes me want to “shop” from this crate when I wrap gifts in the coming months!

Here are some tips for you:

 📌Vintage soda crates are fairly easy to find at antique stores and they’re usually pretty reasonably priced. You can even find some that are super inexpensive, if they’re in less-than-great condition! (I love them all!😁)
 📌Keep an eye out at garage sales and thrift stores. You never know when someone might be getting rid of a vintage crate!
 📌If vintage isn’t your thing, you can find new, reproduction crates at craft and hobby stores. But I would encourage to consider vintage crates because they have so much more charm and character!✨(How cute is this Grapette crate we found at our beloved @brownsvintagevariety?!😍)

 📌I like to save longer bits of used ribbons, to use again if possible. If you roll them up nicely, that’ll often press any wrinkles out of them from the first use. Tucking them into the little crate cubbies helps keep them contained and rolled up, and will make me more likely to grab them and use them on smaller packages in the future. 
 📌I make fun new gift tags every year, but Bartley and I usually save most of them to reuse from year to year. It’s easy to do if they’re tied onto the bows (rather than stuck on) and bonus, it’s fun to see what little notes we wrote on them in years past!
 📌We allllllways save floral picks and little faux greenery and berries and reuse them! There’s no reason to throw them away and many of them aren’t just for Christmas but can be used to wrap gifts for many winter occasions (birthdays, weddings, etc). Tuck a little sprig of some winter greenery under your bow to add that extra little bit of somethin’ special!

Hope these tips have given you some new ideas!

Making your own bracelets can be such a fun and relaxing creative project and bonus….you can actually wear your creations when you’re done!

As you can see in the video, I’ve already made 10 bracelets from these two bead kits and there are enough beads for me to make at least 16 more (and that’s not counting the seed beads in the kits).

That makes the bracelets less than $1 each!!👏🏻

Some tips to keep costs down:

⭐️ Buying beads in kits is a great way to get more beads for less money. (I’ve linked up several that I’ve bought from Amazon! Find them on my Amazon Storefront or my LikeToKnowIt!) comment BEAD LINK PLEASE and I can DM it to you!
⭐️ You can also buy strung beads from craft stores, which allows you to only buy exactly what specific beads you want. However, this is a bit more expensive than buying a kit so be sure to wait for them to go on sale!
⭐️ Sometimes you can save money by buying a larger spool of the stretchy cord, if you know you’re going to be making a lot of bracelets.
⭐️ You could gather a few friends and each of you bring one bead kit to share and then everyone could mix and match and make bracelets together!! Wouldn’t that be so fun, and bonus, you’d all leave with a bracelet stack!

I shared a quick reel awhile back, with instructions for how I like to make these bracelets, or for more detailed instructions in real time, check out my ‘bracelet making’ saved highlight.

Hope this helps! Happy making, friends!

Painting large pieces requires lots of back and forth….painting details up close and then backing away to view it as the viewers will, once the piece is hanging on the wall in someone’s home. If you only ever look at it up close, it’s easy to get lost in the details and lost perspective on the painting as a whole. 

I feel like there’s a life lesson in there somewhere. 😉

It sometimes feels like a bit of a dance in the studio…step forward and paint some details, step back and take it all in as a whole. Step forward and paint some details, step back and take it all in as a whole. Repeat as needed until the dance…er…the painting is finished!😁

In other news, ‘Operation Paint More Large Paintings in 2024’ is well underway!

Pro Tip: When your friend who has a gorgeous ravioli mold invites you over to make homemade freshly milled wheat ravioli with a bacon ricotta filling, just GO!😁

My buddy, @brookeannettebroadbent, taught me how to make fresh ravioli this week, and goodness it was fun! And also, so delish!

We used kamut from @unsifted.kc for the dough and the filling was a recipe from @burntbuttertable. The beautiful wooden ravioli mold is from @johnfrancisdesigns.

The video shows you what happened the first time I ever ran a piece of dough through a pasta roller!🤣

Honestly, just using a @kitchenaidusa mixer was something I’ve wanted to do since I was a teenager watching @marthastewart on her first ever TV show! We don’t have a stand mixer, and I’ve always wanted to use one but we didn’t need one because I wasn’t a baker….until April 2022 when I found @unsifted.kc and started milling our own fresh flour and baking!! So I guess you could say, I had a dream come true this week!😂 Thank you, Brooke!!😘

Some things I learned making ravioli:
 📍Running dough through the pasta attachment takes a little practice!
 📍You don’t want to press too hard with the brush when making pockets in the dough for the filling, or you might poke a hole. 
 📍You don’t want to overfill the ravioli but you do want it full  enough that no air is in the ravioli so it doesn’t burst when boiling. 
 📍Well-floured dough ensures it won’t stick in your mold.
 📍You’ve got to give it a good slam down on the counter to loosen the ravioli! (I spared you that sound in the video!🤣)
 📍When you trim off the extra dough around the ravioli, you can roll that out again, and use up those scraps!
 📍Making ravioli is FUN!!

Have you ever tried it? Do you want to now?😁

Thanks for such a fun morning, Brooke, and for sharing your knowledge and experience with me! We thoroughly enjoyed every bite of our ravioli!

I know it can seem harsh to paint over something I spent so much time painting in the first place, but sometimes painting over a piece is necessary!

Believe me, when I first started painting more than 4 years ago, it would have been unthinkable to paint over a finished piece of artwork! 

But as I’ve grown as an artist, I’ve come to realize that painting over something ok or maybe even something good, makes room for the possibility of painting something that might end up being GREAT!

And not only that, but if a painting has been sitting here for awhile and hasn’t sold, it’s taking up space and it’s doing no one any good. 

I have a responsibility to the Lord, to be a good steward of all that He’s given me, and that includes my art supplies! Painting over older paintings gives me the opportunity to practice good stewardship!

Painting over something that hasn’t sold after a year or more, allows me to put those canvases to good use and give them another opportunity to be beautiful and hopefully loved in someone else’s home!

Now then, who’s excited about more bird paintings in the works???🙋🏻‍♀️

Oh, and one other thing….I’m going through and removing paintings from the website to paint over. So, if there’s one you’ve had your eye on for awhile, you might want to grab it before it gets painted over!🩵
